00:45:05.747 --> 00:45:07.330
AUDIENCE: Could you
speak a little bit

00:45:07.330 --> 00:45:11.100
about the Ethereum
DAO hacking issue that

00:45:11.100 --> 00:45:13.490
happened-- what
happened, actually,

00:45:13.490 --> 00:45:17.622
and then what the effect was
on blockchain technology.

00:45:17.622 --> 00:45:18.580
WILLIAM MOUGAYAR: Yeah.

00:45:18.580 --> 00:45:25.799
I wrote last week a 3,000-word
analysis of it in terms of what

00:45:25.799 --> 00:45:27.840
I thought happened and
what we can learn from it.

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:31.840
I think what happened
is unfortunate.

00:45:31.840 --> 00:45:33.040
It was a hack.

00:45:33.040 --> 00:45:34.890
I don't know the details.

00:45:34.890 --> 00:45:35.920
It was a hack.

00:45:35.920 --> 00:45:39.070
Somebody exploited a weakness
in the smart contract

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:43.380
that the DAO had implemented
which allowed that hacker

00:45:43.380 --> 00:45:48.810
to move funds to a
child DAO for no reason

00:45:48.810 --> 00:45:53.030
than just being a bad person.

00:45:53.030 --> 00:45:57.450
And I think what we
can really take away

00:45:57.450 --> 00:46:01.220
from it is really the lessons
more than what happened

00:46:01.220 --> 00:46:03.290
and should have happened.

00:46:03.290 --> 00:46:07.170
And the lesson is
that it's not easy.

00:46:07.170 --> 00:46:09.100
It's really about money.

00:46:09.100 --> 00:46:12.860
Programming money is not
for the faint of heart.

00:46:12.860 --> 00:46:15.810
It is not a trivial thing.

00:46:15.810 --> 00:46:18.130
And the biggest lesson
is that, again, we

00:46:18.130 --> 00:46:21.270
have to walk before we can run.

00:46:21.270 --> 00:46:24.820
So maybe there was too
much money in there.

00:46:24.820 --> 00:46:27.820
You don't need $150
million to do an experiment

00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:32.000
on whether you can do
autonomous funding of companies

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:34.390
and projects.

00:46:34.390 --> 00:46:37.470
You can have-- $1 million is
enough, or maybe $10 million

00:46:37.470 --> 00:46:40.760
is enough in small chunks,
and giving away half a million

00:46:40.760 --> 00:46:42.900
at a time.

00:46:42.900 --> 00:46:47.052
So by taking all that big
money, it raised the attention.

00:46:47.052 --> 00:46:49.510
If I walked into this room and
I told you I have $1 million

00:46:49.510 --> 00:46:56.975
in my pocket, I won't feel safe
walking outside on El Camino

00:46:56.975 --> 00:46:58.830
if everybody knew
I had $1 million

00:46:58.830 --> 00:47:00.550
in my pocket or somewhere.

00:47:00.550 --> 00:47:03.900
So it drew attention,
unfortunately.

00:47:03.900 --> 00:47:10.380
Now, the good thing is that it's
calling now for more lessons,

00:47:10.380 --> 00:47:12.730
for more best practices.

00:47:12.730 --> 00:47:14.165
Fundamentally, Ethereum is fine.

00:47:14.165 --> 00:47:16.390
There's nothing
wrong with Ethereum.

00:47:16.390 --> 00:47:22.070
It just happened-- this is
like a micro manifestation

00:47:22.070 --> 00:47:27.690
of the Carlota Perez principle
that we always overshoot,

00:47:27.690 --> 00:47:30.860
and then we retract,
and then we're good.

00:47:30.860 --> 00:47:32.970
Because we don't know
what the boundaries are.

00:47:32.970 --> 00:47:35.340
And the DAO was like,
we pushed the boundaries

00:47:35.340 --> 00:47:38.931
a little too hard, and we
hit a wall, and we got hurt.

00:47:38.931 --> 00:47:40.430
So now we know
there's a wall there.

00:47:40.430 --> 00:47:41.592
Let's not go there.

00:47:41.592 --> 00:47:43.550
And we're going to do
some things a bit better.

00:47:43.550 --> 00:47:48.420
So that's what-- I always look
at this in a positive light.

