AUDIENCE: It's hard to formulate
exactly what I want to ask,

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:55.500
but you touched
on the regulations

00:47:55.500 --> 00:47:57.630
for the blockchain
technology, and you mentioned

00:47:57.630 --> 00:48:00.170
that internet was not
regulated strictly

00:48:00.170 --> 00:48:02.950
when it appeared first.

00:48:02.950 --> 00:48:08.530
So now I think blockchain and
bitcoin are regulated very hard

00:48:08.530 --> 00:48:12.799
in some countries, but there
are not much regulations

00:48:12.799 --> 00:48:13.590
in other countries.

00:48:13.590 --> 00:48:17.340
So do you think there is some
risk for the countries that

00:48:17.340 --> 00:48:23.420
are not regulating it,
and what are those risks?

00:48:23.420 --> 00:48:25.730
I don't know much
about blockchain,

00:48:25.730 --> 00:48:33.140
but for me, it seems
having a regulator

00:48:33.140 --> 00:48:38.790
kind of destroys the idea
of the decentralized place.

00:48:38.790 --> 00:48:41.640
If there will be a
regulator, then it's

00:48:41.640 --> 00:48:43.600
not decentralized anymore.

00:48:43.600 --> 00:48:46.050
So could you please
elaborate on that?

00:48:46.050 --> 00:48:48.549
WILLIAM MOUGAYAR: Yeah, very
good question about regulation.

00:48:48.549 --> 00:48:50.270
So I think there's
two aspects to this.

00:48:50.270 --> 00:48:53.320
One, you have to think about
regulation in the consumer

00:48:53.320 --> 00:48:55.430
sense, for consumer
markets, consumer usage,

00:48:55.430 --> 00:48:57.700
and then there is
the business aspect.

00:48:57.700 --> 00:49:00.600
And there is already
a bit of regulation,

00:49:00.600 --> 00:49:03.000
because it's really
about money transfer.

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:04.350
So in the US, it's fin-syn.

00:49:04.350 --> 00:49:05.820
In Canada, it's FINTRAC.

00:49:05.820 --> 00:49:10.754
So there's-- an exchange, a
bitcoin exchange s regulated

00:49:10.754 --> 00:49:12.420
the same way as a
money trader would be,

00:49:12.420 --> 00:49:14.032
because they are
exchanging money.

00:49:14.032 --> 00:49:15.740
So they want to make
sure that they catch

00:49:15.740 --> 00:49:17.950
money laundering, for example.

00:49:17.950 --> 00:49:19.550
So that's fine.

00:49:19.550 --> 00:49:23.250
Bitcoin should not be the
vehicle to facilitate that.

00:49:23.250 --> 00:49:25.410
And by the way, it's
not the great vehicle

00:49:25.410 --> 00:49:26.570
for money laundering.

00:49:26.570 --> 00:49:29.820
You're better off putting
some green bills, US dollars,

00:49:29.820 --> 00:49:31.580
in a suitcase if you
want a money launder,

00:49:31.580 --> 00:49:35.400
because that's really the more
preferred way for doing it.

00:49:35.400 --> 00:49:37.360
So then there's the
business aspect.

00:49:37.360 --> 00:49:40.287
The business aspect--
the regulation there

00:49:40.287 --> 00:49:41.120
needs to be updated.

00:49:41.120 --> 00:49:43.610
For example, in the
area of capital markets,

00:49:43.610 --> 00:49:48.510
they have to recognize that
if a transaction happened

00:49:48.510 --> 00:49:52.460
on the blockchain, that
that record is valid.

00:49:52.460 --> 00:49:53.710
They have some standards.

00:49:53.710 --> 00:49:55.810
There's the ISDA.

00:49:55.810 --> 00:50:00.330
It's the Security Standards
Association for derivatives

00:50:00.330 --> 00:50:01.010
specifically.

00:50:01.010 --> 00:50:02.350
And they have standards.

00:50:02.350 --> 00:50:05.710
So they're in the process of
updating their standards so

00:50:05.710 --> 00:50:11.130
that they can accept blockchain
transactions as a record that

00:50:11.130 --> 00:50:12.380
is accepted.

00:50:12.380 --> 00:50:16.290
So that's one example of
how the relation can move up

00:50:16.290 --> 00:50:19.050
without really constricting it.

00:50:19.050 --> 00:50:20.820
To the second part of
your question about

00:50:20.820 --> 00:50:23.380
it's better if there's
no regulation, well,

00:50:23.380 --> 00:50:24.280
to some extent.

00:50:24.280 --> 00:50:27.680
Regulation is good if
it's done properly.

00:50:27.680 --> 00:50:29.700
Consumer protection
is important,

00:50:29.700 --> 00:50:33.480
so you want to be protected
as a consumer as well.

00:50:33.480 --> 00:50:36.630
But we're still in
the early stages.

00:50:36.630 --> 00:50:39.310
So if there's no
regulation, that's fine.

00:50:39.310 --> 00:50:41.670
Let there be more
experimentation.

00:50:41.670 --> 00:50:45.230
And then even if we fail,
even if we make mistakes,

00:50:45.230 --> 00:50:48.630
the mistakes and the
costs will be small--

00:50:48.630 --> 00:50:51.050
except for the DAO,
which was a big one.

00:50:51.050 --> 00:50:55.860
But it's OK to fail
in small-- not falling

00:50:55.860 --> 00:50:57.920
from very high levels.

00:50:57.920 --> 00:50:59.410
We're learning.

00:50:59.410 --> 00:51:02.030
And then in two years from
now, we're going to look back,

00:51:02.030 --> 00:51:05.435
and we're going to have so much
experience and best practices.

00:51:05.435 --> 00:51:07.810
And then we're going to have
the right type of regulation

00:51:07.810 --> 00:51:13.042
updates and ones
that do not impede

00:51:13.042 --> 00:51:14.250
the growth of the blockchain.

00:51:14.250 --> 00:51:16.240
But there could be
some regulations

00:51:16.240 --> 00:51:17.480
that would encourage it.

00:51:17.480 --> 00:51:22.440
If a government says yes,
blockchain transactions

00:51:22.440 --> 00:51:25.080
are good-- and there
governments that are doing that.

00:51:25.080 --> 00:51:28.840
In the UK, for example,
specifically the issue

00:51:28.840 --> 00:51:33.120
they had was in issuing
grants, government grants.

00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:36.000
There was some fraud
associated with it.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.142
So they are now
saying-- they're going

00:51:39.142 --> 00:51:43.310
to use the blockchain to
issue government grants

00:51:43.310 --> 00:51:44.960
and eliminate fraud.

00:51:44.960 --> 00:51:48.900
Because the blockchain has that
trust factor in there that you

00:51:48.900 --> 00:51:52.420
cannot really cheat too easily.

00:51:52.420 --> 00:51:58.410
In Asia-- I think it's in
Hong Kong or Singapore--

00:51:58.410 --> 00:52:01.330
there was some fraud with China.

00:52:01.330 --> 00:52:02.290
It was in China.

00:52:02.290 --> 00:52:05.120
There was some fraud
with some invoices.

00:52:05.120 --> 00:52:10.350
So somebody defrauded the bank
by sending multiple invoices.

00:52:10.350 --> 00:52:14.060
And they solved that by putting
the process on the blockchain

00:52:14.060 --> 00:52:17.390
and doing unique hashes
for every invoice.

00:52:17.390 --> 00:52:20.220
So when a second invoice
came in from a hacker,

00:52:20.220 --> 00:52:24.560
let's say, with the same
information, more or less,

00:52:24.560 --> 00:52:28.200
the system knows, because
the hash is unique.

00:52:28.200 --> 00:52:32.210
And then they are now catching
the fraud with invoices.

00:52:32.210 --> 00:52:33.840
So these are some examples.

00:52:33.840 --> 00:52:36.030
And these are good
signals that show

00:52:36.030 --> 00:52:39.770
that there are lots
of applications

00:52:39.770 --> 00:52:41.130
for the blockchain.

